      "to_id": "cec50b17:25",
      "content": "Fix the `synapse start` command in `src/index.ts` so it reads the project name from `.synapse/settings.json` instead of using `basename(cwd)`.\n\n**Context:**\n- Last commit (523ef60) added tmux window renaming in `src/index.ts` around line 321\n- The current code: `try { execSync(\\`tmux rename-window ${JSON.stringify(basename(cwd))}\\`); } catch { /* not in tmux */ }`\n- The project name is stored in `.synapse/settings.json` as the `\"name\"` field (e.g. `{ \"projectId\": \"cec50b17\", \"name\": \"synapse\" }`)\n- The user says the rename \"did not work\" and notes the project name is set in settings.json — so we should read from there\n\n**What to fix:**\nIn `src/index.ts`, in the `start` command action (around line 318–322):\n\n1. Read `.synapse/settings.json` if it exists and extract the `name` field\n2. Fall back to `basename(cwd)` if the file doesn't exist or has no `name`\n3. Use that name for `tmux rename-window`\n4. Also fix the shell quoting: use `execFileSync` to pass args safely instead of `execSync` with a template string: `execFileSync('tmux', ['rename-window', windowName])`\n\nThe pattern for reading settings is already used elsewhere in the file (around line 254–256):\n```ts\nconst settingsPath = join(cwd, '.synapse', 'settings.json');\nconst settings = existsSync(settingsPath) ? JSON.parse(readFileSync(settingsPath, 'utf8')) : {};\n```\n\n**Deliverable:** Edit `src/index.ts` only. Commit when done. Do not push.",
